article.headline: Marquette 69, Air Force 65
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Travis Diener played the part of a stone-faced basketball assassin to perfection against the Air Force Academy Falcons. Diener scored 34 points, hitting five 3-pointers, to power Marquette to a 69-65 victory Tuesday night in a wild shootout for the championship of the Black Coaches Association Classic. At one point Diener nailed three consecutive 3-pointers to put his team ahead for good at 55-50. "Diener killed us," Air Force coach Chris Mooney said. "He's a great player. That proved to be the turning point." Diener's 34 points set a single game Classic record, topping the 31 points that Mike Helms of Oakland, Mich., scored last year against San Diego. His three-game total of 77 points beat Helms' 2003 record of 72 points. Diener, named the tournament's most valuable player, said he never knows how many points he'll score because "I just take what they give me." "I expect to play well every night," he said. "I just try to go out there and play to the best of my ability and give 110 percent." Dameon Mason added 12 points and Steve Novak 10 for Marquette (3-0), which won all of its three games in the eight-team, three-day tournament. Matt McCraw and Nick Welch both scored 15 points for Air Force (2-1). McCraw scored all of his points on 3-pointers, making all five he tried. Air Force led 48-44 after Jared Dillinger and Antoine Hood hit back to back 3-pointers. But Diener hit his three straight for a 55-50 Marquette lead with 9:08 left to play. Diener's three long range baskets were part of an 11-2 run in which he scored all of Marquette's points. Hood, who scored 13 points, was awed by Diener. "It's kind of like a bad nightmare when you watch someone take over the game like that," Hood said. Diener, who made 5-of-9 3-point shots, hit his fifth trey with 2:41 left for a 63-57 Marquette lead. With 24 seconds left to play McCraw made his own fifth 3-pointer to pull the Falcons within three points at 68-65. But with 16.7 seconds left Diener hit one of two free-throws for the game's final point. Marquette coach Tom Cream called Diener "the straw that stirs our drink" but said he was excited that so many other players contributed to a tough victory over a solid Air Force team. "We got a lot of guys in the machine who are carrying their weight," he said. Marquette led 35-32 after a close, hard-fought first half in which the score was tied six times. Joining Diener and Hood on the All-Tournament team were Marcus Jackson of Marquette, Lorenzo Gordon of Illinois State and Air Force's Welch. The teams had not met since Dec. 28, 1987 when Marquette beat Air Force 80-52 in Milwaukee. The Golden Eagles have beaten the Falcons 13 consecutive times. Air Force will return to action Sunday when the Falcons host Alcorn State of Mississippi. The Braves (1-2) will meet Wyoming in Laramie on Friday night before traveling to Colorado. ^------= On the Net: Marquette University Golden Eagles: http://www.gomarquette.com Air Force Academy Falcons: http://airforcesports.collegesports.com Alcorn State University Braves: http://alcornsports.com Black Coaches Association: http://www.bcasports.org
